1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,500
Friday, four-fifty PM. A merge request lands —
"add the production env file."

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:09,000
The reviewer's tired, with eight more in the queue.

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,500
Inside this diff: a database password, a JWT secret,
a live Stripe key, an AWS access key —

4
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:17,000
everything policy says must never hit the repo.
This is how secrets ship.

5
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
MR Sentinel is the reviewer that never gets tired.

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:25,500
The moment an MR opens, MR Sentinel — a Google Agent
Development Kit agent on Cloud Run — wakes up.

7
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:30,000
Watch it actually run.

8
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:35,000
Read the log — this is the agent running.

9
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:41,000
"ADK evaluate, via GitLab MCP": it spins up
GitLab's own MCP server and calls it directly —

10
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:48,000
get-merge-request, get-merge-request-diffs,
list-pipelines, each one going through MCP.

11
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:55,000
It hands all that to Gemini, on Vertex AI, which
judges the diff against fifteen rules at once

12
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:02,000
and records a structured verdict. Every MCP call
logged and replayable — about thirty seconds end to end.

13
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:07,000
And here's what it leaves on the merge request
that started this.

14
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,500
Verdict: block. Score: zero out of ten.

15
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:18,000
It cites no-secrets-in-diff by rule ID — mapped to
SOC 2, ISO 27001, OWASP — and quotes the exact lines,

16
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:24,000
opens a remediation issue with a checklist,
and labels it blocked-compliance.

17
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Every action ties back to a named control.

18
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:34,000
That's one MR. Here's the portfolio — the last
thirty days, every MR scored,

19
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:42,000
most blocked on compliance, the top failing rules,
each one a control mapped to an audit framework.

20
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Click any one and you're in the audit log —

21
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
every outcome, every control mapping, the timeline.
At year-end, that's just… there.

22
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Three deliberate choices. GitLab's MCP server for
the reads — a portable tool surface:

23
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:02,000
the same agent points at gitlab.com or a
self-hosted instance with no rewiring.

24
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:08,000
ADK, because governance needs a real tool-calling
loop and a structured verdict, not a chat reply.

25
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:13,000
And Gemini on Vertex, so no diff
ever leaves Google Cloud.

26
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:20,000
One honest seam: reads run through MCP, write-backs
use GitLab's REST API — the Duo server can't post yet.

27
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:26,000
Every regulated engineering org has this exact
pain — and most ship the secret anyway.

28
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:32,000
One ADK agent, Gemini for the judgment,
GitLab's MCP server for reach,

29
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:37,000
and one rubric where every rule is a named compliance
control. It ships MIT — fork it, run your own.

30
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:40,000
The audit trail is just the byproduct. MR Sentinel.
